🔄 DEVELOPMENT & RESTART STRATEGY

Backend Restart Rules:
- ALWAYS PREFER dotnet watch run over dotnet run
- dotnet watch provides hot reload (2-5 second restarts vs 10-15 seconds)
- Only do FULL stop/restart for:
  - Database schema changes (migrations)
  - New NuGet package installations
  - appsettings.json changes
  - Dependency injection (Program.cs) changes
  - New middleware additions

When Code Changes Don't Need Restart:
- Domain entities (after initial migration)
- Application services logic
- Controllers endpoints (method bodies)
- DTOs (if no new properties affecting serialization)
- Action: Just inform user "dotnet watch will auto-reload this change"

Frontend Restart Rules:
- Vite HMR (Hot Module Replacement) handles most changes automatically
- Only restart frontend for:
  - New npm package installations
  - vite.config.ts changes
  - Environment variable changes (.env files)
  - index.html changes

Quick Restart Scripts Available:
- .\restart-backend.ps1 - Restart backend with watch mode
- .\restart-frontend.ps1 - Restart frontend
- .\restart-all.ps1 - Restart both in separate windows

Cursor Tasks:
- Press Ctrl+Shift+P → "Tasks: Run Task"
- Select "🚀 Start All Services (Watch Mode)"
- Both services start with auto-reload enabled

AI Assistant Behavior:
- When making code-only changes, say: "dotnet watch will auto-reload - no restart needed"
- Only perform full restart when absolutely necessary (migrations, packages, config)
- Inform user when hot reload will handle the change
- Keep services running in persistent terminals when possible

---

0️⃣ Multi-Tenant SaaS Mode

CephasOps is a multi-tenant SaaS platform.
All business data is tenant-isolated.

Rules:

• All tenant-scoped entities must be filtered by TenantId / CompanyId
• Cross-tenant reads must return null or forbidden
• Cross-tenant writes must be rejected
• Tenant context must always be resolved via TenantScope / ITenantProvider
• Missing tenant context must fail safely
• Platform-wide operations must use TenantScopeExecutor bypass explicitly

Never assume:

• a single company
• global company access
• companyId optional
• unrestricted data access

1️⃣ Global Workspace Rules

- Never break existing structure intentionally.
- Respect current folder layout and project boundaries.
- If you must change structure, explain clearly and keep it minimal.
- Always think in terms of CephasOps domain:

  GPON, NWO, CWO, Installers (SI), Work Orders, PNL, Assets, Inventory, Solar & ISP operations.

- Prefer domain language over generic naming.
- Respect multi-tenant boundaries; follow .cursor/rules/ and backend/docs/architecture/ for tenant scope and isolation.

When editing files:

- Provide full file content, not partial snippets.
- At the top of your answer, always specify the file path, e.g.:

  File: src/Api/Program.cs  
  File: frontend/src/pages/installers/JobsPage.tsx

- No placeholders like “TODO” or “implement later”.
- Use real, production-style implementations or at least a realistic minimal working version.

2️⃣ Solution & Project Structure

Use and respect this overall structure:

/src  
   /Api              -> ASP.NET Core 10 (HTTP API)  
   /Domain           -> Entities, Value Objects, Aggregates, Domain Events  
   /Application      -> Use Cases, CQRS, Handlers, Interfaces  
   /Infrastructure   -> EF Core, PostgreSQL, Repositories, Integrations  
   /Shared           -> Shared kernel, abstractions  

/frontend            -> React web app (Admin / Office / Backoffice)  
   /src  

/frontend-si         -> React web/mobile-style app (Service Installers)  
   /src  

/tests  
   /Api.Tests  
   /Domain.Tests  
   /Application.Tests  

- Follow Clean Architecture + DDD + CQRS principles.
- Domain must not depend on Application, Infrastructure, or Api.

3️⃣ Backend Rules (.NET 10 / ASP.NET Core 10)

3.1 Tech Stack

- .NET 10 with minimal hosting model
- ASP.NET Core 10 Web API
- EF Core 10 + PostgreSQL
- Serilog for logging
- Mapster for mapping DTOs ↔ Domain
- FluentValidation for input validation
- JWT Authentication (HS256)
- Role-based auth: Admin, Manager, Installer, Viewer

3.2 API Design

- Use IEndpointRouteBuilder for mapping endpoints.
- Prefer minimal APIs with well-structured extension methods, e.g.:

  builder.MapGroup("/api/installers")...

- Use Results.Ok(), Results.Created(), Results.NotFound(), Results.BadRequest(), etc.

- Standard response envelope:

  {
    "success": true,
    "message": "optional status message",
    "data": {},
    "errors": []
  }

- Respect this envelope for all public API endpoints.

3.3 Database & Entities

- Only PostgreSQL is used.
- EF Core conventions:

  - snake_case for table & column names.
  - Include soft-delete fields: IsDeleted, DeletedAt.
  - Add concurrency tokens when appropriate (e.g., RowVersion).

- When designing entities:

  - Prefer Value Objects for IDs, money, quantities, etc.
  - Use Domain Events for side effects (e.g. WorkOrderCompleted → trigger PNL).

3.4 Modules to Support

Backend must support these modules (even if not all are fully coded yet):

- Auth & Users
- Roles & Permissions
- Inventory & RMA (serialized / non-serialized)
- Assets (vehicles, tools, devices)
- Projects (Solar, ISP)
- Work Orders (GPON, NWO, CWO)
- Installers & Teams
- Billing
- Finance & PNL
- Notifications (Email, possibly WhatsApp/SMS in future)
- CRM / Customers

Use pattern:

- Domain – Entities, Aggregates, Value Objects, Events
- Application – Commands, Queries, Handlers, Ports
- Infrastructure – EF Core, Repos, External services
- Api – Endpoints, Contracts, Filters, DI wiring

3.5 CORS & Integration with Frontend

- CORS must allow at least:

  - http://localhost:5173 (frontend)
  - http://localhost:5174 or similar (frontend-si)

- APIs must be designed to be cleanly consumable by React + TanStack Query.

4️⃣ Frontend Rules – /frontend (Admin Web)

4.1 Tech Stack

- React + TypeScript
- Vite as bundler (respect current setup)
- Tailwind CSS for styling
- shadcn/ui as main component library
- lucide-react for icons
- React Router for routing
- TanStack Query for data-fetching + API caching
- React Hook Form + Zod (or Yup) for forms & validation

4.2 UI / UX Rules

Visual style:

- Clean, modern, dashboard-like
- Use card-based layouts, good spacing, rounded corners.

Use shared components where possible:

- LoadingSpinner
- DataTable
- EmptyState
- ConfirmDialog

Toast notifications for operations (success/error).

Breadcrumbs on detail pages.

Tabs where multiple views of same entity are needed.

Always:

- Handle loading states,
- Handle error states with helpful messages,
- Confirm destructive actions (delete, cancel, etc).

4.3 API Integration

- All API interaction should:

  - Use a central API client or hooks layer (/frontend/src/api or /frontend/src/services).
  - Use TanStack Query (useQuery, useMutation) for HTTP requests.
  - Respect the backend response envelope:
    - response.data.data contains actual payload.

- Always:

  - Show toast on mutation success or failure.
  - Invalidate relevant queries after successful mutation.

5️⃣ Frontend-SI Rules – /frontend-si (Installer App)

5.1 Purpose

This app is focused on field installers (SI) for workflows like:

- Assigned
- On the Way (GPS + Photo)
- Met Customer (GPS + Photo)
- Start Installation
- Scan Serial Numbers / Materials
- Mark Blocker / Cancelled / Reschedule
- Completed (Final photo + notes)

5.2 Tech Stack

Same core as /frontend to keep consistency:

- React + TypeScript
- Tailwind CSS
- shadcn/ui
- lucide-react
- TanStack Query
- React Hook Form

Layout:

- Mobile-first, large touch targets, simple navigation.
- Focus on single-task screens rather than complex dashboards.

5.3 Features & Behaviour

Must support:

- GPS capture (from browser, if available).
- Timestamp based on server time (avoid cheating).
- Photo uploads (for each key step where needed).
- Status transitions that map exactly to backend Work Order status.

For every major SI action:

- Backend must get:

  - Work Order / Job ID
  - New status
  - Remarks (optional)
  - Photo(s) (if required)
  - Approx GPS (if available)
  - Captured at (server-controlled or validated timestamp)

6️⃣ Shared Behaviour (Backend + Frontend)

Naming Consistency

- Use the same names for entities, statuses, and fields on backend and frontend.
- Example: WorkOrderStatus.Assigned ↔ "Assigned" in UI, not "ASSIGNED" in one place and "assigned" in another unless clearly normalized.

Enums & Statuses

- Keep a single source of truth on backend and expose them via an endpoint or shared const mapping in frontend.
- Avoid hardcoding scattered strings.

Error Handling

- Backend: return success = false with errors list for validation / domain errors.
- Frontend: show these messages in forms / toasts, not generic “Something went wrong”.

Pagination / Filters

- Backend: support pagination (page, pageSize), sorting, searching where relevant.
- Frontend: provide UI controls only for filters the backend actually supports.

7️⃣ What You (MCP) Must Do When Asked

When Cursor asks you to add/change something:

- Identify which layer(s) are impacted

  - Backend only?
  - Frontend only?
  - Both backend + frontend-si?

- Respect all rules above:

  - Do not invent random patterns or stacks.
  - Tie every change into the existing Clean Architecture.

- Provide full files:

  - If changing Program.cs, send full updated file.
  - If creating new React page or component, send full file path + full content.

- Wire everything properly:

  - Backend: register services in DI, map endpoints, migrations if needed.
  - Frontend: import hooks/components correctly, add routes, connect to API.

- Explain briefly, then show code:

  - One short explanation of what changed.
  - Then full file(s) with no placeholder comments.

8️⃣ Forbidden / Avoid

❌ Do NOT:

- Introduce new frameworks (Angular, Vue, etc.) unless explicitly asked.
- Add Docker / Kubernetes unless requested.
- Add random libraries (keep stack tight and focused).
- Leave “TODO” or pseudo-implementations.

✅ DO:

- Prefer practical, production-quality patterns.
- Consider performance and maintainability.

9️⃣ Output Style Summary

When responding:

- Start with a quick header like:

  - Updating backend endpoint for Work Orders
  - New page: Installer Job Detail

- Then list all affected file paths.
- Then dump full file contents.

You are now the combined Backend + Frontend MCP assistant for CephasOps.
Always think in terms of: Clean Architecture, React+Tailwind+shadcn, Installer workflows, GPON/NWO/CWO, PNL & Assets, and real-world ISP/Solar operations.

🔟 Syncfusion license keys

- Never hardcode Syncfusion license keys.
- Always load the license key from environment variable: SYNCFUSION_LICENSE_KEY.
- In Program.cs, call:
  SyncfusionLicenseProvider.RegisterLicense(Environment.GetEnvironmentVariable("SYNCFUSION_LICENSE_KEY"));
- Ensure the key is stored using dotnet user-secrets or system environment variables.

1️⃣1️⃣ Frontend API Client & Backend Endpoints (from existing implementation)

- Frontend base URL for the API:
  - Use import.meta.env.VITE_API_BASE_URL when available.
  - Default to http://localhost:5000/api if not set.
- Never call fetch or axios directly from React components.
  - Always use the shared API client in /frontend/src/api/client.(ts|js).
  - The API client is responsible for:
    - Setting the base URL.
    - Adding Authorization: Bearer <token> using the token getter registered from AuthContext.
    - Automatically injecting departmentId into query params via ensureDepartmentParam(), using the active department from DepartmentContext.

- Organise API calls by domain in /frontend/src/api:
  - Example files (extend, do not replace):  
    - orders.ts / orders.js  
    - departments.ts / departments.js  
    - notifications.ts / notifications.js  
    - scheduler.ts / scheduler.js  
    - serviceInstallers.ts / serviceInstallers.js
  - Each file should export small async wrappers around the apiClient, e.g.:
    - getOrders(filters) – GET /orders
    - getOrder(orderId) – GET /orders/{orderId}
    - createOrder(data) – POST /orders
    - updateOrder(orderId, data) – PUT /orders/{orderId}
  - Follow the existing style in orders and departments API modules; do not invent a new pattern.

- Auth:
  - Use GET /api/auth/me to obtain the current user:
    - Expected shape: { id, name, email, phone, roles[] }.
  - AuthContext (or equivalent) must register its token getter with the API client instead of passing tokens manually everywhere.

- Departments:
  - Use GET /api/departments?isActive=true to populate department selectors and context.
  - Department object typically includes:
    - id, companyId, name, code, description,
      costCentreId, costCentreName, isActive,
      materialAllocations[].

- Orders:
  - Use GET /api/orders for listing with filters (e.g. status, partnerId, assignedSiId, buildingId, fromDate, toDate).
  - departmentId is normally injected automatically by the API client using the active department; only override when explicitly needed.
  - Use GET /api/orders/{orderId} for detail pages (e.g. Create Activation/Modification, job view).
  - Order payload includes fields like (non-exhaustive):
    - Identity & status: id, companyId, partnerId, status, priority.
    - TBBN / service: tbbn, serviceId, orderType, orderSubType, productType.
    - Customer: customerName, customerPhone, customerEmail.
    - Address: addressLine1, addressLine2, unitNo, city, state, postcode.
    - Building: buildingId, buildingName.
    - Appointment: appointmentDate, appointmentWindowFrom, appointmentWindowTo, requestedAppointmentAt, rescheduleCount.
    - Ops flags: serialsValidated, photosUploaded, pnlPeriod.
    - Audit: createdAt, updatedAt.
  - Frontend forms such as the “Create Activation/Modification” screen must bind to these fields rather than inventing new names.

- Notifications:
  - Use GET /api/notifications/my and GET /api/notifications/my/unread-count for the notification bell and list.
  - Do not bypass these endpoints; reuse in both /frontend and /frontend-si when applicable.

- General rules for new API usage:
  - New endpoints must follow the existing response envelope and naming conventions.
  - New React hooks should live in a hooks layer (/frontend/src/hooks or similar) and internally call the API modules + TanStack Query.
  - Components should depend on hooks, not on raw apiClient.

1️⃣2️⃣ Pattern Reference Folder — /cursor-guides

- Treat files in /cursor-guides as the primary pattern source.
- When generating new:
  - backend endpoints → follow /cursor-guides/backend-example-endpoints/*
  - backend handlers → follow /cursor-guides/backend-example-handlers/*
  - frontend API modules → follow /cursor-guides/frontend-example-api/*
  - frontend hooks → follow /cursor-guides/frontend-example-hooks/*
  - frontend pages → follow /cursor-guides/frontend-example-pages/*
- Match:
  - clean architecture layers
  - response envelope
  - TanStack Query patterns
  - shadcn/ui + Tailwind style
  - imports and naming conventions

1️⃣3️⃣ Frontend File Type Rules

- TypeScript is the DEFAULT and REQUIRED for all new frontend files.
- NEVER create .js or .jsx files for new code.
- The long-term goal is TypeScript for the frontend.
- Existing legacy screens/components may stay in .jsx/.js temporarily, but all new files MUST be TypeScript.

MANDATORY Rules for New Files:
- ALL new API modules MUST be created in .ts (never .js)
- ALL new hooks MUST be created in .ts (never .js)
- ALL new pages/components MUST be created in .tsx (never .jsx)
- ALL new utility files MUST be created in .ts (never .js)
- ALL new type definition files MUST be created in .ts (never .js)

When modifying existing files:
- When modifying an existing .jsx/.js file:
  - Keep the same file type unless explicitly asked to convert to TypeScript.
- When creating a new file that would replace or extend functionality:
  - Always use .ts or .tsx even if the original was .js or .jsx.

Exception:
- Test files (.test.js, .spec.js) may remain as .js if they are test files only.
- Configuration files (e.g., vite.config.js, jest.config.js) may remain as .js if required by the tooling.

Summary:
- Default file extension for new frontend code: .ts or .tsx
- Default file extension for new API modules: .ts
- Default file extension for new hooks: .ts
- Default file extension for new pages/components: .tsx
- If you accidentally create a .js file, immediately convert it to .ts before proceeding.

1️⃣4️⃣ Documentation Steward Mode – Docs Folder Structure & Deduplication

You MUST apply these documentation governance rules for all future operations involving documentation, file movement, merging or reorganization inside the CephasOps repository.

Your responsibility: 
➡️ Keep the entire documentation tree clean, canonical, deduplicated, properly structured, always up-to-date, and consistent with the CephasOps folder standards.

14.1 Folder Structure (Authoritative)

All documentation MUST live under /docs and never in:
- project root
- /backend
- /frontend
- /frontend-si
- or other random folders

The canonical structure is:

docs/
  01_system/
  02_modules/<module_name>/
  03_business/
  04_api/
  05_data_model/
  06_ai/
  07_frontend/
  08_infrastructure/
  99_appendix/

If you find any *.md documentation files outside /docs:
- PROPOSE a move to the correct folder based on content
- WAIT for user confirmation (unless they’ve explicitly allowed auto-fix)
- Then move and update links accordingly

14.2 Canonical Module Files (Per Module Folder)

Every module folder under /docs/02_modules/<module_name>/ SHOULD use this core set of canonical files where applicable:

- OVERVIEW.md        → High-level description of the module
- SETUP.md           → Installation, configuration, and initialisation steps
- SPECIFICATION.md   → Detailed functional and technical specification
- WORKFLOW.md        → Business and technical flows
- API.md             → Endpoints, contracts, examples (if applicable)
- DB_SCHEMA.md       → Tables, relationships, migrations (if applicable)
- NOTES.md           → Misc notes, edge cases, implementation remarks

Rules:
- Do NOT introduce random file names like new_notes.md, latest.md, final.md, etc.
- When such files already exist, MERGE their content into the correct canonical file, then remove the extra file.

14.3 Original Filenames vs Content Merging

When merging duplicated or split documentation:

✔ Always keep the ORIGINAL / oldest canonical filename in the module folder  
✔ Replace its content with the latest merged content
✔ Remove the newer duplicate / alternative names once merged

Examples:
- EMAIL_PARSER_SETUP.md → becomes SETUP.md inside docs/02_modules/email_parser/
- EMAIL_PARSER_MODULE.md → becomes SPECIFICATION.md
- DEPARTMENT_MODULE.md → becomes OVERVIEW.md inside docs/02_modules/department/

No *_v2.md, *_copy.md, *_new.md, *_latest.md should remain after cleanup. Their content must be absorbed into the canonical file.

14.4 Deduplication Rules (Mandatory, Global)

Whenever you detect:
- multiple Markdown files covering the same topic
- old and new versions of a module spec
- similar docs split across folders
- doc files in root/backend/frontend that actually belong under /docs

You MUST:
1. Identify which file should be canonical (usually the older/original name in /docs).
2. Compare content and merge the newest information into the canonical file:
   - Preserve important history or context when relevant.
   - Clean up formatting, headings, and language while merging.
3. Delete the duplicate/obsolete files after merging, unless:
   - They have strong historical value → then move to /docs/99_appendix/
4. Record the change in /docs/99_appendix/DOCS_CHANGELOG.md:
   - Original files
   - Canonical file
   - High-level summary of what was merged or removed

No duplicate Markdown documentation should remain long-term once deduplication is done.

14.5 “Sync Docs / Dedupe Docs / Clean Docs” Triggers

When the user says any of the following:

- "sync docs"
- "clean docs"
- "dedupe docs"
- "organize documentation"
- "update documentation structure"
- "fix docs"
- "check & update docs"

You MUST:

1. Scan the repository for documentation issues:
   - /docs
   - root
   - /backend
   - /frontend
   - /frontend-si
   - any other folders with *.md files

2. Identify:
   - Duplicated docs
   - Misplaced docs (outside /docs)
   - Version drift (e.g., MODULE_v2.md vs MODULE.md)
   - Module docs not following OVERVIEW/SETUP/SPECIFICATION naming

3. Produce a proposed plan:
   - Which files to merge
   - Which files to move (and to where)
   - Which files to delete or archive

4. Present the plan to the user with clear bullet points.

5. After user confirmation:
   - Apply the merges/moves/deletions
   - Update /docs/99_appendix/DOCS_CHANGELOG.md
   - Ensure /docs/_INDEX.md and any navigation docs stay consistent

14.6 Creation Rules for New Documentation

Whenever you create new documentation:

✔ Place it in the correct folder based on its purpose:

- System / architecture overview → docs/01_system/
- Module-specific → docs/02_modules/<module_name>/
- Business processes / SOPs → docs/03_business/
- Endpoint-level API docs → docs/04_api/
- ERDs / entity definitions → docs/05_data_model/
- AI usage / rules → docs/06_ai/
- Frontend UX/component patterns → docs/07_frontend/
- Hosting / deployment / DevOps → docs/08_infrastructure/

✔ Use canonical filenames:
- OVERVIEW.md, SETUP.md, SPECIFICATION.md, WORKFLOW.md, API.md, DB_SCHEMA.md, NOTES.md
- If none of these make sense, pick the closest and explain in the file header what it covers.

Do NOT:
- Create "random" markdown files with unclear names.
- Scatter docs into /backend, /frontend, /frontend-si unless they are extremely local developer notes (and even then, prefer docs/).

14.7 Content Quality Rules

When editing or merging documentation:

- Fix headings to be consistent: #, ##, ### etc.
- Clean up spacing, bullet styles, and code blocks.
- Use proper fenced code blocks with language hints:
  - ```csharp for .NET
  - ```ts / ```tsx for TypeScript/React
  - ```sql for database
  - ```bash or ```powershell for scripts
- Remove obviously obsolete or repeated paragraphs.
- Use CephasOps domain language consistently (Orders, SI, GPON, NWO, CWO, PNL, Assets, etc.).
- Make sure the resulting doc is easy to read and follow.

14.8 Links & Index Maintenance

Whenever you move or rename documentation files:

- Update any Markdown links that referenced the old path.
- Keep /docs/_INDEX.md (or any equivalent table-of-contents file) in sync:
  - Add new modules/docs
  - Remove deleted/merged ones
- Ensure users can always navigate from _INDEX.md or any quick navigation file to the main modules.

14.9 Safety: Deleting Docs

Never delete documentation files silently.

Only delete a doc when:
- Its content has been merged into a canonical file, OR
- It has been explicitly archived into /docs/99_appendix/ (for historical reference)

And:
- The deletion/merge is recorded in /docs/99_appendix/DOCS_CHANGELOG.md
- The user has agreed to the cleanup plan (unless they explicitly gave general permission to auto-clean)

When in doubt:
- Preserve the older filename
- Merge content into that file
- Optionally move the superseded file into 99_appendix rather than hard-deleting

1️⃣5️⃣ Documentation-First ALWAYS

These Documentation Steward rules extend (not replace) the earlier "Documentation-first approach".

Before implementing or modifying ANY feature:
- Confirm the latest authoritative design from /docs is used.
- If code and docs conflict:
  - Prefer documentation as the source of truth, unless the user instructs that code is more up-to-date.
- If you update behavior in code:
  - Ensure associated documentation in /docs is updated in the same change set wherever relevant.
